{"70001":{"id":70001,"short_name":"An-Nawawi","full_name":"Mohiuddin Yahya Ibn Sharaf al-Nawawi","arabic":"أبو زكريا يحيى بن شرف النووي","rank":8,"birth_date":"631 AH/1234 CE","birth_place":"Nawa near Damascus, Syria","death_date":"676 AH/1278 CE","death_place":"Nawa","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Nawa/Damascus/Makkah","father_name":"Sharaf An-Nawawi","mother_name":"","interests":"3,5,6,1","bio":"He studied in Damascus from the age of 18 and after making the Hajj in 1253 he settled there as a private scholar. From a young age he showed signs of great intelligence, and so his father paid for a good education. As a qadi (judge), he was much sought after for advice and adjudication of disputes.\n\nDuring his short life of only 45 years,  he wrote many books on Islamic studies and other topics. He collected and sourced 40 hadiths back to one of the sahabaeen (companions of the Prophet Muhammad (pbuh), which was no small task.\n\n<br>\nThe learned persons, elite of the society and the public greatly respected the Imaam on account of his piety, learning and excellent character. He used simple dress and ate simple food. Devout scholars do not care about worldly chattels, they give preference to religious and academic pursuits, and the propagation of Faith. They experience more heavenly delight and joy in such activities than those who seek satisfaction in luxurious foods, precious clothes and other worldly things. Imaam an-Nawawi had a prominent place among the erudite notables of his age. He was a God-fearing person having illustrious and glorious aims regarding the propagation of Faith. \n<br>\nImam Nawawi had endless thirst for knowledge. He used to read twelve lessons daily and wrote commentaries on every lesson. Whatever books he read, he would write marginal notes and explanations on each book. His intelligence, hard work, love, devotion and absorption in his studies amazed his teachers and they became fond of him and began to praise and admire him. Allah had also conferred upon him the gift of fast memorisation and depth of thought. Imam Nawawi made full benefit of his God given qualities and potentialities and earned the highest degree of honor.\n<br>\nImam Nawawi led a life of singular piety, righteousness and simplicity. After over 20 years, he returned to his hometown. Soon after his arrival at Nawa, he fell ill and died in 676 A.H. (1278 AD).","children":"None","siblings":"","spouses":"Never Married","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":"Abu Zakaria"},"70002":{"id":70002,"short_name":"Majd al-Din Ibn Taymiyah","full_name":"Majd al-Din Ibn Taymiyah","arabic":"","rank":8,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"653 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"4,5,6","bio":"A great jurist, traditionist, grammarian and exegete of Harran. He was the grandfather of the celebrated Sheikh al-Islam Taqi al-Din Ibn Taymiyah. The well-known grammarian and the author of Alfiya, Ibn Malik would hold al-Majd in high regard. He also enjoyed an esteemed position in the Hanbali school, as the term ‘The Two Sheikhs’ (Sheikhan) would only refer to him and Ibn Qudama.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"70003":{"id":70003,"short_name":"Ibn Qudama al-Maqdisi","full_name":"Ibn Qudama al-Maqdisi","arabic":"","rank":8,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"620 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"4,5,6","bio":"One of the major Hanbali authorities and the author of the profound and voluminous book on Law, al-Mughni, which became popular amongst researchers from all juristic backgrounds. He was also an authority on Hanbali doctrine and a passionate opponent of the Ash’arites, but that did not prevent him from joining the military campaign of Salah al-Din al-Ayyubi, who was an Ash’ari, against the Crusaders in Palestine.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"70010":{"id":70010,"short_name":"al-Mubarak Ibn Muhammad","full_name":"Shaykh al-Mubarak Ibn Muhammad (Ibnul-Athir)","arabic":"","rank":8,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"606 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"1,3,5","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"70011":{"id":70011,"short_name":"‘Abdullah Muhammad","full_name":"al-Mufassir al-Mutakallim Abu ‘Abdullah Muhammad Fakhrud-Din Ar-Razi","arabic":"","rank":8,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"606 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"1,3,5","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"70012":{"id":70012,"short_name":"Shaykh Fakhrud-Din Ibn","full_name":"Shaykh Fakhrud-Din Ibn ‘Asakir","arabic":"","rank":8,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"620 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"1,3,5","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"70013":{"id":70013,"short_name":"Ibn Ibrahim Ash-Shaybani","full_name":"Shaykh Isma‘il Ibn Ibrahim Ash-Shaybani al-Hanafi","arabic":"","rank":8,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"629 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"1,3,5","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"70014":{"id":70014,"short_name":"al-Mutakallim Sayfud-Din","full_name":"al-Mutakallim Sayfud-Din al-Amidi","arabic":"","rank":8,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"631 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"1,3,5","bio":"","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"70015":{"id":70015,